    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense on the morale side, but i'm more worried about the actual math. if i'm already running on thin margins, won't a higher wage just force me to cut staff or raise prices so much that my customers leave? it feels like the \"increased buying power\" thing is more of a theory than something that actually helps a small shop like mine stay afloat.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I completely understand your concerns about balancing the books with a higher minimum wage. Innovation can be a great ally—consider streamlining operations or introducing higher-margin menu items to offset increased labor costs without overhauling the price structure drastically. As for relying on increased buying power translating directly into better business, while retail patterns can shift, the true impact would depend on how price-sensitive your customers are. If they value your cafe's experience over convenience, you might not see adverse effects. Additionally, attracting and retaining more skilled staff with a higher wage could enhance service quality and customer satisfaction, leading to word-of-mouth marketing and potentially new patronage. Careful consideration of your staffing strategy alongside cost adjustments will be key to navigating the transition.",
